Prosper Lending Data Analysis Project¶

by Anh Tran Thi Ngoc¶

Introduction¶

Prosper Marketplace is America's first peer-to-peer lending marketplace. Borrowers request personal loans on Prosper and investors (individual or institutional) can fund anywhere from 2,000 USD to 40,000 USD per loan request.

This notebook is aimed at exploring the Prosper Lending data set which contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.

The main research question of this project is: What affects the borrower's interet rate?

Cleaning issues¶

  • ListingCreationDate has a data type of object instead of datetime
  • Many columns with missing values
  • Some columns have a blank space in column name. Ex: ProsperRating (numeric), ProsperRating (Alpha), ListingCategory (numeric),..

Missing Values¶

There are 2 critical variables in this data set that I would like to further analyze are only available after July 2009. Therefore, only the loans originated after July 2009 are included in this analysis.

I'm most interested in figuring out what features affect the borrower's interest rate.

# Change the List Category from numeric to text

def encode_category(ListingCategoryNumeric):
    if ListingCategoryNumeric==0:
        category = 'Not Available'
    if ListingCategoryNumeric==1:
        category = 'Debt Consolidation'
    if ListingCategoryNumeric==2:
        category = 'Home Improvement'
    if ListingCategoryNumeric==3:
        category = 'Business'
    if ListingCategoryNumeric==4:
        category = 'Personal Loan'
    if ListingCategoryNumeric==5:
        category = 'Student Use'
    if ListingCategoryNumeric==6:
        category = 'Auto'
    if ListingCategoryNumeric==7:
        category = 'Other'
    if ListingCategoryNumeric==8:
        category = 'Baby&Adoption'
    if ListingCategoryNumeric==9:
        category = 'Boat'
    if ListingCategoryNumeric==10:
        category = 'Cosmetic Procedure'
    if ListingCategoryNumeric==11:
        category = 'Engagement Ring'
    if ListingCategoryNumeric==12:
        category = 'Green Loans'
    if ListingCategoryNumeric==13:
        category = 'Household Expanses'
    if ListingCategoryNumeric==14:
        category = 'Large Purchases'
    if ListingCategoryNumeric==15:
        category = 'Medical/Dental'
    if ListingCategoryNumeric==16:
        category = 'Motorcycle'
    if ListingCategoryNumeric==17:
        category = 'RV'
    if ListingCategoryNumeric==18:
        category = 'Taxes'
    if ListingCategoryNumeric==19:
        category = 'Vacation'
    if ListingCategoryNumeric==20:
        category = 'Wedding Loans'
    return category



df_clean['ListingCategory']=df_clean['ListingCategoryNumeric'].apply(encode_category)

def boxgrid1(x, y, **kwargs):
    """ Quick hack for creating box plots with seaborn's PairGrid. """
    default_color = sns.color_palette()[0]
    sns.boxplot(x, y, color = default_color)
    plt.xticks(rotation =90)

Interest rate have a correlation with Proper Rating and Average Credit Score. However, this relationship is only clear if the rating or credit score is really high or really low. In other words, if borrowers are very high risk, they are penalized by higher interest rates. On the other hand, if borrowers are very low credit risk, they entitile low borrowing rate. For customer wtih medium risk, there is no clear pattern.

When borrowers own a home, the lender tends to evaluate them less risky than others because of their higher capacity to repay the loan. What do we observe in this multivariate investigation?¶

I extended my investigation of interest rate against credit rating by looking at the impact of categorical features. The multivariate exploration showed that there is a negative relation ship between the credit rating and interest rate. The higher credit rating, the lower interest rate. However, there is no clear different in interest rate of borrower who have the same credit rating but different listing category or employment status. When borrowers own a home, they pay lower interest if their employment status is employed, fulltime or self-employed. It is completely inverse for unemployed borrowers.
